{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"00130e8e-c126-47b3-b65f-59a7a06fa398","content":"## Analysis\n\nThe project is a simple .NET 8 app. The report confirms targets skip correctly and compilation is fast (<500ms) — the overhead is **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation. Visual Studio avoids this because it keeps MSBuild nodes in-memory.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**1. Enable the MSBuild Server** (biggest win for .NET 8+):\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\n\nThis keeps MSBuild worker nodes alive between invocations, eliminating cold-start overhead — the same approach VS uses.\n\n**2. Use `dotnet watch build`** for the inner loop:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\nStays resident, watches for file changes, and rebuilds incrementally without process restart.\n\n**3. Ensure node reuse is enabled** (default, but verify it's not disabled):\n\n```bash\n# Make sure this is NOT set in your environment:\n# MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=1\n```\n\n**4. Use `--no-restore`** when you know packages haven't changed:\n\n```bash\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\n\nSkips the NuGet restore evaluation step entirely.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The root cause is that `dotnet build` spawns a new process and re-evaluates the project graph each time. The MSBuild Server (`DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`) directly addresses this by keeping nodes warm between builds. For rapid edit-build cycles, `dotnet watch` eliminates the problem entirely by staying resident.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0c74073c-ed17-4cae-aac1-20d2dcec57bf","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer is reporting that CLI builds with `dotnet build` are slow for incremental builds, even when nothing has changed. Visual Studio builds the same project almost instantly.\n\nThe key insight from the report is:\n> The overhead seems to come from MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph on every CLI invocation.\n\nThe reason Visual Studio is faster is that it keeps an MSBuild server process running (it uses the MSBuild node reuse / server model). When you run `dotnet build` from the CLI, by default it:\n1. Starts a new dotnet process\n2. Loads MSBuild\n3. Evaluates the project\n\n\n4. Determines nothing needs to be built\n5. Exits\n\nThe solution is to enable the MSBuild server, which keeps MSBuild nodes alive between builds just like Visual Studio does. Starting with .NET 8, you can activate this by setting `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` or using the `-tl` flag to get the same persistent build server behavior that eliminates the startup overhead on subsequent builds. enabling the MSBuild server with `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` eliminates startup overhead. For iterative development, `dotnet watch build` is probably the most impactful since it keeps the process alive between changes, avoiding repeated initialization costs. and keeps MSBuild nodes alive between CLI invocations, much like Visual Studio does. I should also mention using `dotnet watch` for faster incremental builds during development, and potentially adding a `.rsp` file to reduce evaluation overhead by consolidating common build options.","outputTokens":1399,"requestId":"1C31:183D91:B762C8:D461F0:69F3FA8E"},"id":"3010e08f-27d5-4d4d-a41d-4cb8c957ad8d","timestamp":"2026-05-01T00:58:18.919Z","parentId":"cf2a3d19-947c-4a2f-bd1f-2574e7e6c92c"}
